<!-- ========== COMPOUND OVERVIEW ========== -->
<hr class="sep">
<h2>GHK-Cu at a Glance</h2>

<div class="cd cp">
  <div class="tg">Compound Profile</div>
  <h3>GHK-Cu (Glycyl-L-Histidyl-L-Lysine Copper)</h3>
  <p style="font-size:14px;margin-bottom:0;"><strong>Sequence:</strong> Gly-His-Lys + Cu(II) &nbsp;|&nbsp; <strong>Type:</strong> Naturally occurring tripeptide-copper complex &nbsp;|&nbsp; <strong>Molecular Weight:</strong> 403.93 g/mol &nbsp;|&nbsp; <strong>Discovered:</strong> 1970s by Dr. Loren Pickart &nbsp;|&nbsp; <strong>Routes:</strong> Topical cream/serum, subcutaneous injection, microneedling, nasal spray &nbsp;|&nbsp; <strong>FDA Status:</strong> Not approved as a drug; widely used in cosmetics &nbsp;|&nbsp; <strong>Primary Actions:</strong> Collagen synthesis, wound healing, anti-inflammatory, gene modulation</p>
</div>

<p>GHK-Cu was first isolated from human plasma in the 1970s by Dr. Loren Pickart (<a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/18789600/">Pickart, 2008</a>). The "Cu" refers to copper. GHK binds copper(II) ions with extremely high affinity, and it's this copper-bound form that's biologically active.</p>

<p>Your body produces GHK-Cu naturally, but levels drop sharply with age. At 20, plasma concentrations sit around 200 ng/mL. By 60, that's fallen to roughly 80 ng/mL.</p>

<p>That decline correlates with visible aging, slower wound healing, and reduced tissue repair capacity. For a deeper compound profile, visit <a href="https://peptidearc.com">PeptideArc</a>.</p>

