<h3>Gene Expression Modulation</h3>

<p>A landmark study found GHK-Cu significantly affected <strong>4,000+ genes</strong>, roughly 6% of the human genome (<a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/23019195/">Campbell et al., 2012</a>). That's not a typo. A single tripeptide shifting thousands of genes toward a younger expression pattern.</p>

<p>The upregulated genes handle tissue repair, collagen synthesis, and antioxidant defense. The downregulated ones control inflammation, tissue destruction, and fibrosis.</p>

<div class="d-t">
  <div class="s">Key Finding</div>
  <p>GHK-Cu acts as a master switch, shifting gene expression toward a younger, more regenerative pattern. This is one of the broadest gene-modulatory effects documented for any single peptide.</p>
</div>

<h3>Copper Delivery</h3>

<p>Copper is an essential trace element involved in dozens of enzymatic reactions. GHK-Cu delivers it in a controlled, bioavailable form rather than as free copper ions, which can cause oxidative damage.</p>

<table class="tbl">
<thead><tr><th>Copper-Dependent Process</th><th>Enzyme</th><th>Relevance</th></tr></thead>
<tbody>
<tr><td><strong>Collagen cross-linking</strong></td><td>Lysyl oxidase</td><td class="g">Critical for skin firmness</td></tr>
<tr><td><strong>Antioxidant defense</strong></td><td>Superoxide dismutase</td><td class="g">Protects against UV damage</td></tr>
<tr><td><strong>New blood vessels</strong></td><td>Various</td><td class="g">Wound healing support</td></tr>
<tr><td><strong>Nerve repair</strong></td><td>Various</td><td class="y">Less studied but promising</td></tr>
</tbody>
</table>

<h3>Stem Cell Recruitment</h3>

<p>GHK-Cu attracts mesenchymal stem cells to sites of injury. These stem cells can differentiate into fibroblasts, osteoblasts, and chondrocytes.</p>

<p>That multi-lineage recruitment may explain why GHK-Cu accelerates healing across so many different tissue types. It's not just patching wounds; it's calling in the repair crew.</p>

<!-- ========== SKIN BENEFITS ========== -->
